<p>
A <b>graphing calculator</b> (also <b>graphics calculator</b> or <b>graphic=
 display calculator</b>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hand=
held_computer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Handheld computer">handheld c=
omputer</a> that is capable of plotting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Graph_of_a_function" title=3D"Graph of a function">graphs</a>, solvin=
g <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simultaneous_equations" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Simultaneous equations">simultaneous equations</a>, =
and performing other tasks with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Va=
riable_(mathematics)" title=3D"Variable (mathematics)">variables</a>. Most =
popular graphing calculators are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
rogrammable_calculator" title=3D"Programmable calculator">programmable calc=
ulators</a>, allowing the user to create customized programs, typically for=
 scientific, engineering or education applications. They have large screens=
 that display several lines of text and calculations.
</p>
