<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:TI-84_Plus_IO.jpeg" class=3D"=
mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/com=
mons/thumb/b/b6/TI-84_Plus_IO.jpeg/250px-TI-84_Plus_IO.jpeg" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"250" height=3D"172" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"2360" data-file-height=3D"1620"></a><figcaption>Typical ports on a grap=
hing calculator. These contain a 2.5&nbsp;mm I/O port for connecting to oth=
er calculators and a Mini USB port for connecting to a PC.</figcaption></fi=
gure>
<p>Most graphing calculators, as well as some non-graphing <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_calculator" title=3D"Scientific calcula=
tor">scientific calculators</a> and programmer's calculators can be program=
med to automate complex and frequently used series of calculations and thos=
e inaccessible from the keyboard.
</p><p>Programming is often performed on a computer and subsequently upload=
ed to the calculator. Common tools for this process include PC link cables =
and corresponding software for the specific calculator, configurable text e=
ditors or hex editors, and specialized programming environments supporting =
various languages on the computer side.
</p><p>Earlier calculators used magnetic cards and similar media for progra=
m storage; however, increased onboard memory has made internal storage the =
prevailing method. Some modern calculators also support external memory car=
ds.
</p><p>A cable and/or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IrDA" title=
=3D"IrDA">IrDA</a> transceiver connecting the calculator to a computer make=
 the process easier and expands other possibilities such as on-board spread=
sheet, database, graphics, and word processing programs. The second option =
is being able to code the programs on board the calculator itself.  This op=
tion is facilitated by the inclusion of full-screen text editors and other =
programming tools in the default feature set of the calculator or as option=
al items.  Some calculators have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q=
WERTY" title=3D"QWERTY">QWERTY</a> keyboards and others can be attached to =
an external keyboard which can be close to the size of a regular 102-key co=
mputer keyboard.  Programming is a major use for the software and cables us=
ed to connect calculators to computers.
</p><p>The most common programming languages used for calculators are simil=
ar to keystroke-macro languages and variants of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/BASIC" title=3D"BASIC">BASIC</a>. The latter can have a large=
 feature set=E2=80=94approaching that of BASIC as found in computers=E2=80=
=94including character and string manipulation, advanced conditional and br=
anching statements, sound, graphics, and more including, of course, the hug=
e spectrum of mathematical, string, bit-manipulation, number base, I/O, and=
 graphics functions built into the machine.
</p><p>Most calculators capable to being connected to a computer can be pro=
grammed in assembly language and machine code, although on some calculators=
 this is only possible through using exploits. The most common assembly and=
 machine languages are for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TMS9900=
" title=3D"TMS9900">TMS9900</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
uperH" title=3D"SuperH">SH-3</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Zilog_Z80" title=3D"Zilog Z80">Zilog Z80</a>, and various <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motorola" title=3D"Motorola">Motorola</a> chips (e.=
g. a modified <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/68000" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"68000">68000</a>) which serve as the main processors of t=
he machines although many (not all) are modified to some extent from their =
use elsewhere. Some manufacturers do not document and even mildly discourag=
e the assembly language programming of their machines because they must be =
programmed in this way by putting together the program on the PC and then f=
orcing it into the calculator by various improvised methods.
</p><p>Other on-board programming languages include purpose-made languages,=
 variants of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eiffel_(programming_l=
anguage)" title=3D"Eiffel (programming language)">Eiffel</a>, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forth_(programming_language)" title=3D"Forth (p=
rogramming language)">Forth</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Lisp_(programming_language)" title=3D"Lisp (programming language)">Lisp<=
/a>, and Command Script facilities which are similar in function to batch/s=
hell programming and other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scripti=
ng_language#Glue_languages" title=3D"Scripting language">glue languages</a>=
 on computers but generally not as full featured.  Ports of other languages=
 like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BBC_BASIC" title=3D"BBC BASI=
C">BBC BASIC</a> and development of on-board interpreters for <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fortran" title=3D"Fortran">Fortran</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/REXX" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"REXX=
">REXX</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AWK" title=3D"AWK">AWK=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl" title=3D"Perl">Perl</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_shell" title=3D"Unix shell=
">Unix shells</a> (e.g., <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bash_(Uni=
x_shell)" title=3D"Bash (Unix shell)">bash</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Z_shell" title=3D"Z shell">zsh</a>), other shells (<a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DOS" title=3D"DOS">DOS</a>/<a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_9x" title=3D"Windows 9x">Windows 9x</a>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OS/2" title=3D"OS/2">OS/2</a>, and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_NT" title=3D"Windows NT">Wi=
ndows NT</a> family shells as well as the related <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/4DOS" title=3D"4DOS">4DOS</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Take_Command_Console" title=3D"Take Command Console">4NT</a> a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/4OS2" title=3D"4OS2">4OS2</a> a=
s well as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DIGITAL_Command_Language=
" title=3D"DIGITAL Command Language">DCL</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/COBOL" title=3D"COBOL">COBOL</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title=3D"C (programming language)">C=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language=
)" title=3D"Python (programming language)">Python</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tcl" title=3D"Tcl">Tcl</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Pascal_(programming_language)" title=3D"Pascal (programming =
language)">Pascal</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delphi_(pro=
gramming_language)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Delphi (programming lang=
uage)">Delphi</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ALGOL" title=3D=
"ALGOL">ALGOL</a>, and other languages are at various levels of development=
.
</p><p>Some calculators, especially those with other PDA-like functions hav=
e actual operating systems including the TI proprietary OS for its more rec=
ent machines, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DOS" title=3D"DOS">D=
OS</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_CE" title=3D"Windo=
ws CE">Windows CE</a>, and rarely <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Windows_NT_4.0_Embedded" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Windows NT 4.0 Embe=
dded">Windows NT 4.0 Embedded</a> et seq, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Linux" title=3D"Linux">Linux</a>. Experiments with the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI-89" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"TI-=
89">TI-89</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI-92_series" title=
=3D"TI-92 series">TI-92</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI-92=
_Plus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"TI-92 Plus">TI-92 Plus</a> and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voyage_200" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Voyage 200">Voyage 200</a> machines show the possibility of installing =
some variants of other systems such as a chopped-down variant of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CP/M#The_16-bit_world" title=3D"CP/M">CP/M-6=
8K</a>, an operating system which has been used for portable devices in the=
 past.
</p><p>Tools which allow for programming the calculators in C/C++ and possi=
bly Fortran and assembly language are used on the computer side, such as <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HPGCC" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"HPGCC">HPGCC</a>, TIGCC and others. Flash memory is another means of co=
nveyance of information to and from the calculator.
</p><p>Most graphing calculators have on-board spreadsheets which usually i=
ntegrate with Microsoft Excel on the computer side.  At this time, spreadsh=
eets with macro and other automation facilities on the calculator side are =
not on the market. In some cases, the list, matrix, and data grid facilitie=
s can be combined with the native programming language of the calculator to=
 have the effect of a macro and scripting enabled spreadsheet.
</p>
